00:01:30.640 --> 00:01:32.910
made by Dr. Charles M. Hitchcock

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:37.060
to institute a professorship
at the University of California

00:01:37.060 --> 00:01:41.250
for free lectures upon scientific
and practical subjects.

00:01:41.250 --> 00:01:44.180
Professor Greider,
welcome back to Berkeley.

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:45.370
- Thank you, it's nice to be here.

00:01:45.370 --> 00:01:47.110
- Where were you born and raised?

00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:49.780
- I was born in, actually,
San Diego, California,

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:52.220
but I was raised in Davis, California.

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:53.900
- Looking back, how do
you think your parents

00:01:53.900 --> 00:01:55.950
shaped your thinking about the world?

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.010
- Well my father was a
physicist at UC Davis

00:02:00.010 --> 00:02:03.780
and he very much encouraged
me and my brother

00:02:03.780 --> 00:02:07.200
to be able to follow what
we were interested in

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:09.400
and to try and keep all doors open

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:11.520
and very much encouraged us to be able to

00:02:12.890 --> 00:02:15.940
explore things that interested us.

00:02:15.940 --> 00:02:18.810
So I think that that really shaped

00:02:18.810 --> 00:02:21.590
how I thought about a career.

00:02:21.590 --> 00:02:24.780
- And your mother also
had a PhD from Berkeley.

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:26.750
Both your parents had PhDs from Berkeley.

00:02:26.750 --> 00:02:28.440
- Both my parents had PhDs from Berkeley

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:29.970
although my mother died when I was young

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:31.550
and so it was my father that raised us.

00:02:31.550 --> 00:02:35.150
So his influence on, sort of, where I went

00:02:35.150 --> 00:02:37.070
is what I remember most.

00:02:37.070 --> 00:02:39.750
- Was there a lot of
talk at the dinner table

00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:41.840
about scientific matters?

00:02:42.690 --> 00:02:44.570
- Sometimes, usually about physics,

00:02:44.570 --> 00:02:47.730
which was a little bit above my head,

00:02:47.730 --> 00:02:50.480
but, certainly, it was clear that

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:54.420
being able to pursue what you
were interested in was a goal.

00:02:56.840 --> 00:03:01.840
- Because of your father's
role as a professor,

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:05.230
part of your early
years were spent abroad.

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:08.650
- Yes, he was on sabbatical

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:13.650
at the Max Planck Institute
in Heidelberg when I was 12.

00:03:14.150 --> 00:03:18.310
So I went to Germany and was
put into the German Gymnasium

00:03:18.310 --> 00:03:20.880
and, as a consequence,
learned to speak German

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:22.140
either the hard way or the easy way,

00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:23.760
depending on how you think about it,

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:25.745
just being thrown in and immersed.

00:03:25.745 --> 00:03:28.810
- In biographical material,
I've read about you,

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:33.500
you had an older brother and
your relationship with him

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:37.130
was very important and
both of you developed

00:03:38.234 --> 00:03:41.380
a sense of autonomy and independence,

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:43.420
even by walking to school.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:45.360
- Yeah, walking to school
when we were also in,

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:47.480
when we were young, but also in Germany

00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:49.650
and being able to get around on our own

00:03:49.650 --> 00:03:53.220
through the public transportation
when we were 12 and 13.

00:03:54.161 --> 00:03:57.140
It was important.

00:03:57.140 --> 00:04:00.790
- Were thinking skills, critical thinking,

00:04:00.790 --> 00:04:04.090
just something you absorbed
with the atmosphere,

00:04:04.090 --> 00:04:07.890
a physics professor
father studying abroad,

00:04:07.890 --> 00:04:09.760
even as a young person?

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:12.130
- I never really thought
of it that way so much.

00:04:13.255 --> 00:04:14.560
I didn't think of myself as somebody

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:17.100
that was particularly
good at critical thinking.

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:21.420
I was just trying to follow
things I was interested in.

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:26.390
- In your early years
you had dyslexia, right?

00:04:26.390 --> 00:04:31.390
So you had to develop, drawn
this independence and autonomy

00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:36.390
to figure out how to really cope

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:38.440
to make up for what you couldn't do

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:40.950
with things that you could do very well.

00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:44.270
- Well it wasn't clear what
dyslexia was back then.

00:04:44.270 --> 00:04:46.640
All I knew was that I had to be

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:48.100
taken out of my regular classroom

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:49.670
for this remedial spelling

00:04:49.670 --> 00:04:53.050
and then I had a lot
of trouble in spelling

00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:55.400
and, it wasn't really defined as dyslexia.

00:04:55.400 --> 00:04:57.180
So it wasn't until I
was a little bit older

00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:00.700
and looking back, that it was
clear that it was dyslexia.

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:03.300
So I think that's part of what contributed

00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:06.930
to my feeling like,
maybe I wasn't as bright

00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:09.070
as some of the other kids were,

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:11.690
but if I worked hard, I
could still do what I wanted.

00:05:11.690 --> 00:05:14.450
So that was sort of the
image that I had of myself.

00:05:14.450 --> 00:05:17.460
It was embarrassing to be
sitting in grade school

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:19.080
and have a special teacher come in

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:20.690
and take you out of the classroom

00:05:20.690 --> 00:05:22.350
in front of all of the other kids.

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:25.180
- But you learned to compensate, really,

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:29.350
and develop coping strategies and skills.

00:05:29.350 --> 00:05:32.200
- Later on, they ended
up being very useful.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:34.620
I remember in my high school biology,

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.750
when we had a lot of
memorization with anatomy.

00:05:37.750 --> 00:05:38.964
We were doing anatomy of the cat

00:05:38.964 --> 00:05:43.090
and I found it very
easy to memorize things.

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:44.980
I realized, retrospectively, that that was

00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:47.940
probably because, when I saw a word,

00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:51.050
I couldn't sound out the
word and so, instead,

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:52.740
I would memorize it.

00:05:52.740 --> 00:05:54.880
So that developed those memory skills

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:59.380
that ended up having
advantages in other settings.

00:06:00.510 --> 00:06:03.796
- Did you have any teachers
before you went to college

00:06:03.796 --> 00:06:07.560
that helped further what was

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:10.070
to become your interest in science?

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:13.980
- I was very interested
in biology in high school.

00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:16.910
It wasn't necessarily
something that I said

00:06:16.910 --> 00:06:18.240
I wanted to have a career in.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:21.820
And I wasn't one of the
kids that did science fairs

00:06:21.820 --> 00:06:23.990
or had a chemistry set.

00:06:23.990 --> 00:06:26.140
But when I was a senior in high school,

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:29.310
I thought biology was interesting

00:06:29.310 --> 00:06:32.010
and I was interested,
particularly, in marine biology,

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:35.660
which is what prompted me then
to choose UC Santa Barbara

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:39.060
as the place to go for
my undergraduate work.

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:44.000
- For you, Santa Barbara
was a special place

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
because of a special college
within Santa Barbara.

00:06:49.290 --> 00:06:51.032
Talk a little about that because it seems

00:06:51.032 --> 00:06:56.032
that you really developed
some important skills there.

00:06:56.760 --> 00:06:58.540
- Yeah, so, in addition to applying

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:00.210
to the University of
California at Santa Barbara,

00:07:00.210 --> 00:07:02.630
I also applied to the
College of Creative Studies.

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:06.600
And I knew about this because
there was professor there,

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:10.610
Bea Sweeney, who had been
a colleague of my mother's

00:07:10.610 --> 00:07:13.850
and my father still kept
in contact with the family.

00:07:13.850 --> 00:07:15.470
She was a professor of biology

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:19.180
within this integrated college.

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:24.180
So, literature, science, math,
arts within a small group.

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:29.530
That was particularly wonderful

00:07:29.530 --> 00:07:33.980
because there was a lot
of individual attention.

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:38.720
Each student had an assigned advisor

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:42.140
and you could develop a
curriculum with that advisor

00:07:42.140 --> 00:07:46.170
without necessarily having to
take certain blocks of classes

00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:48.210
as the rest of the university did.

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:50.880
I found that very wonderful

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:54.630
'cause it allowed me to
be able to do experiments

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:58.020
in laboratories earlier
than I otherwise would.

00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:02.230
- You really got into the science

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:07.230
and doing the experiments
across different areas.

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:10.170
Talk a little about that.

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:13.470
- Yeah, so, I remember when Bea
Sweeney, who was my advisor,

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:16.790
said to me as a freshman, she really felt

00:08:16.790 --> 00:08:18.930
that I should be working in a laboratory.

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:21.620
I remember being thrown in as a freshman

00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:23.570
and having all of these
college classes and, again,

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:25.670
thinking that I wasn't as smart

00:08:25.670 --> 00:08:27.230
as all of my other colleagues.

00:08:27.230 --> 00:08:28.550
And I thought, well that
would be overwhelming,

00:08:28.550 --> 00:08:30.580
and she said, "I think you
should try it anyway." (laughs)

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:31.560
(Harry laughs)

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:35.950
And so I did and I started
off in a laboratory

00:08:35.950 --> 00:08:39.970
doing some ecology, beach ecology.

00:08:39.970 --> 00:08:41.980
I quickly learned that,

00:08:41.980 --> 00:08:43.630
although I was interested in biology,

00:08:43.630 --> 00:08:48.630
that area of biology didn't
really fit my way of thinking.

00:08:48.930 --> 00:08:50.600
It was more statistics.

00:08:52.070 --> 00:08:54.140
So then, through Bea Sweeney,

00:08:54.140 --> 00:08:57.360
and interactions with her,
she was able to help me

00:08:57.360 --> 00:09:01.860
get into several different
laboratories at Santa Barbara

00:09:01.860 --> 00:09:03.870
and it was when I got into a laboratory

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:06.450
that was doing more biochemistry,

00:09:06.450 --> 00:09:08.670
where one could really
look at what we now call,

00:09:08.670 --> 00:09:10.520
sort of mechanistic interactions,

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:12.310
how you make a change in a system

00:09:12.310 --> 00:09:15.350
and then you can see the
outcome of that change,

00:09:15.350 --> 00:09:18.770
that that really fit my
intellectual way of thinking.

00:09:18.770 --> 00:09:22.030
So that was really a wonderful opportunity

00:09:22.030 --> 00:09:24.100
to test out different areas.

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:25.570
Because sometimes you can't know

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:27.150
what is most interesting to you

00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:29.457
until you're actually in the environment.

00:09:29.457 --> 00:09:33.207
- So it was a matter of self-discovery

00:09:33.207 --> 00:09:36.570
what really worked for you
and, interestingly enough,

00:09:36.570 --> 00:09:41.570
it sounded like you
wanted a physics dimension

00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:44.590
to the biology you
- well certainly

00:09:44.590 --> 00:09:47.470
a physical dimension, yes--
- a physical, yeah.

00:09:47.470 --> 00:09:50.280
But that's what physicists do, right?

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:51.550
Yeah, so that's,

00:09:53.938 --> 00:09:55.190
that's fascinating.

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:58.740
But the structure, the
curriculum structure,

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:01.620
and the mentoring, sort of helped you

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:04.270
find what it is you actually wanted to do.

00:10:04.270 --> 00:10:07.820
That's rare, sometimes, in
undergraduate education.

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:11.550
- Yes, and it also helps because
I also took a year abroad.

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:13.100
Because I already spoke German,

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:16.450
I was able to take a year
abroad at Santa Barbara

00:10:16.450 --> 00:10:17.680
and go and study in Göttingen.

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:20.590
So it was my second year abroad then

00:10:20.590 --> 00:10:23.540
and it allowed me then
to take the courses there

00:10:23.540 --> 00:10:25.990
and fit them into my academic program.

00:10:25.990 --> 00:10:27.580
So, in taking a year abroad,

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:29.200
I still graduated in four years.

00:10:31.449 --> 00:10:32.910
- It sounds like a lotta your experience

00:10:32.910 --> 00:10:36.780
made you observant of people

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:39.380
and different kinds of people, in a way.

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:40.213
Is that fair?

00:10:40.213 --> 00:10:43.750
I mean, to be immersed
in a foreign environment

00:10:43.750 --> 00:10:45.710
at a young age and then doing it again,

00:10:46.970 --> 00:10:50.770
it must have helped make
you an observant person

00:10:50.770 --> 00:10:52.530
of the differences out there.

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:54.560
- Yes, I mean, I think that
that is certainly something

00:10:54.560 --> 00:10:57.950
that I was always aware of is,

00:10:57.950 --> 00:10:59.650
people and interactions with people.

00:10:59.650 --> 00:11:03.120
So, I think that, because I
liked that, I liked going abroad

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:05.190
and the going abroad then helped me

00:11:05.190 --> 00:11:06.720
learn to do that as well.

00:11:06.720 --> 00:11:10.190
- Now, then, after getting your BA,

00:11:10.190 --> 00:11:14.270
you came to Berkeley
as a graduate student.

00:11:14.270 --> 00:11:19.270
Talk about choosing Berkeley
and why you wanted to be here.

00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:24.070
- Well, when I was applying
to various graduate schools,

00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:26.520
again, one has to take standardized tests

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:29.938
and, because of my dyslexia,
first for the GREs,

00:11:29.938 --> 00:11:32.500
sorry, for the SATs and also for the GREs,

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:34.620
I didn't do so well on those.

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:39.700
So, of the 13 places that I applied to,

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:44.520
only two considered me
for the graduate program

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:47.070
and one was Cal Tech and
the other was UC Berkeley.

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:50.370
My advisor, Bea Sweeney, at the time,

00:11:50.370 --> 00:11:52.060
she said, "Oh, you just
wanna go to Berkeley

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:53.300
"because that's where your mother went."

00:11:53.300 --> 00:11:54.930
And she advised me,
instead, to go to Cal Tech

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:56.228
to do something different.

00:11:56.228 --> 00:11:57.830
(both laugh)

00:11:57.830 --> 00:11:59.960
But when I came to interview,

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:03.810
I was very captivated by the
program and, specifically,

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:06.200
my interactions with Elizabeth Blackburn

00:12:06.200 --> 00:12:09.250
during my interview here, and
that's what really swayed me

00:12:09.250 --> 00:12:12.230
to come here rather than Cal Tech.

00:12:13.090 --> 00:12:15.910
- What were the years
that you were at Berkeley

00:12:15.910 --> 00:12:18.570
and what was Berkeley like then,

00:12:18.570 --> 00:12:20.780
just atmospherically, in general?

00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:24.600
- I was here from '83 to '88.

00:12:27.628 --> 00:12:32.410
It was a wonderful, open
intellectual environment

00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:37.040
and I very much liked the interactions

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:41.110
with my classmates in the
molecular biology department.

00:12:42.810 --> 00:12:43.990
People really were interested

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:45.950
in what other people were working on.

00:12:45.950 --> 00:12:48.020
Friends would talk, not just about

00:12:49.300 --> 00:12:51.840
what was going on socially,

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:53.950
but, mostly, it was about experiments.

00:12:56.120 --> 00:13:01.120
There was a lot of
support amongst the group.

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:06.840
So, today, many of my best
friends are still the students

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:09.440
that I was here with at
Berkeley during my PhD.

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:14.080
- I like to ask my guests what they see as

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:17.450
both the skill set and the temperament

00:13:17.450 --> 00:13:22.450
that are important for
the kind of work you do.

00:13:25.120 --> 00:13:26.967
- What they would see or what--

00:13:26.967 --> 00:13:30.650
- What you, looking
back at your own career,

00:13:30.650 --> 00:13:32.570
and doing the work that you do,

00:13:32.570 --> 00:13:35.270
what is the skill set involved?

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:40.480
- Being able to be able
to have the freedom

00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:43.980
to do something that one's interested in

00:13:43.980 --> 00:13:46.850
without, necessarily,
worrying about obstacles.

00:13:46.850 --> 00:13:48.770
I think that that's something that

00:13:48.770 --> 00:13:52.150
is different today than it used to be.

00:13:52.150 --> 00:13:54.680
People are a little bit more
worried these days about,

00:13:54.680 --> 00:13:56.340
what are they gonna do for their career

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:57.860
or what might get in the way.

00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:02.130
But, I certainly felt,
as a graduate student,

00:14:02.130 --> 00:14:05.175
that I just wanted to
do what was interesting

00:14:05.175 --> 00:14:07.520
and I didn't really see

00:14:07.520 --> 00:14:10.520
that there were limitations or obstacles.

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:14.960
Now that may be unique to me
because I learned early on,

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:18.090
perhaps through the dyslexia,
to just put blinders on,

00:14:18.090 --> 00:14:20.080
and when I saw something I couldn't do,

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:22.430
just to ignore the fact
that I couldn't do it.

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:27.430
So it's not clear to me if I
was unique in that setting.

00:14:27.750 --> 00:14:31.770
But, certainly, I felt that
I was extremely encouraged

00:14:31.770 --> 00:14:34.440
to follow what was interesting

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:37.510
and not worry about any consequences.

00:14:37.510 --> 00:14:40.060
- You had some choices once you were here

00:14:40.060 --> 00:14:42.660
in terms of what you would specialize in.

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:46.930
What was your thought processes like?

00:14:46.930 --> 00:14:50.480
Had your experience at
Santa Barbara sort of

00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:55.010
pointed the way, so to speak,
in the choices you made there?

00:14:55.870 --> 00:14:57.405
- I knew from Santa Barbara that

00:14:57.405 --> 00:15:01.580
I liked this sort of
mechanistic way of thinking.

00:15:01.580 --> 00:15:03.900
That was in both biochemistry

00:15:03.900 --> 00:15:06.280
as well as in molecular biology.

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:11.280
But conversations with some of
my mentors at Santa Barbara,

00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:15.370
Kevin Sullivan and David
Asai, were really saying,

00:15:15.370 --> 00:15:20.370
DNA is the way of the
future in terms of where

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:23.710
these kinds of interesting
questions are going to lead.

00:15:23.710 --> 00:15:25.370
So that, then, prompted me to apply

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:27.160
for the department of molecular biology

00:15:27.160 --> 00:15:29.560
rather than to the
department of biochemistry

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:30.720
because, naively, I thought

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:33.230
that there was more of
that in molecular biology.

00:15:33.230 --> 00:15:35.880
It turns out that it was
going on in both departments

00:15:37.016 --> 00:15:39.150
but that's what I was sort of looking for,

00:15:39.150 --> 00:15:42.910
was something where one could study things

00:15:42.910 --> 00:15:46.667
in a very mechanistic way
and understand the DNA.

00:15:48.150 --> 00:15:53.150
- So you decided to work
under Professor Blackburn

00:15:54.350 --> 00:15:59.350
and you became interested in her work

00:15:59.510 --> 00:16:03.440
and extending her work in telomeres.

00:16:04.410 --> 00:16:09.410
So help us understand what a telomere is,

00:16:12.940 --> 00:16:13.810
yes.

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:16.200
- Yean, so it's the very
end of the chromosome

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:20.420
and Liz had been working on
this for a number of years

00:16:20.420 --> 00:16:22.240
and it was something that I hadn't

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:23.940
really heard very much about.

00:16:23.940 --> 00:16:25.240
So I was particularly interested in it

00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:28.460
because it was a little
bit out of the main stream.

00:16:28.460 --> 00:16:30.740
But they are the ends of chromosomes,

00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:32.630
the functional unit at
the ends of chromosomes

00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:35.940
which are essential for
protecting the chromosome ends.

00:16:35.940 --> 00:16:37.240
- So it's like a little cap.

00:16:37.240 --> 00:16:40.230
- A little cap that
protects the chromosome end.

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:41.540
But it turns out that, in addition

00:16:41.540 --> 00:16:43.350
to protecting the chromosome end,

00:16:43.350 --> 00:16:47.450
it's important for maintaining
the length of the chromosome.

00:16:47.450 --> 00:16:49.680
That was something that, at the time,

00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:54.680
Liz and others were recently
aware of, that the way that,

00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:58.550
When you copy a whole
chromosome, it turns out

00:16:58.550 --> 00:17:00.070
that the way you copy a chromosome,

00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:02.590
the very end of that
chromosome, the telomere,

00:17:02.590 --> 00:17:05.240
can't be completely copied to the end.

00:17:05.240 --> 00:17:08.170
So there was this mystery about how it is

00:17:08.170 --> 00:17:10.100
that the end of the
chromosome can be maintained.

00:17:10.100 --> 00:17:13.760
Why isn't it just that
the telomeres get shorter

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:16.690
and shorter and shorter
every time a cell divides?

00:17:16.690 --> 00:17:18.890
That was certainly the prediction.

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:23.650
So, we were interested in
how that problem is overcome.

00:17:25.490 --> 00:17:29.950
- As you begin this work and
really extend it over time,

00:17:29.950 --> 00:17:32.710
you're, and I've learned
this in interviewing

00:17:32.710 --> 00:17:34.330
the scientists who've come aboard,

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:36.480
you're actually on the back

00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:40.800
of people who have preceded
you and made discoveries.

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:45.090
So let's just talk a
little about that so, in,

00:17:45.090 --> 00:17:46.980
let me see if I have this here.

00:17:46.980 --> 00:17:51.980
In the '30s, what did
Muller and McClintock do

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:55.070
that set the stage for
what you were doing?

00:17:55.070 --> 00:17:57.630
- The function of telomeres,
in terms of this protective cap

00:17:57.630 --> 00:18:00.540
that's what H.J. Muller
and Barbara McClintock

00:18:00.540 --> 00:18:02.530
showed, was that,

00:18:02.530 --> 00:18:03.950
Mueller was working in Drosophila

00:18:03.950 --> 00:18:06.870
and McClintock in corn or maize,

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:09.050
showed that there must be
something protective at the end

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:12.500
because when you break
that chromosome end,

00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:15.650
that you get the chromosome
is either degraded

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:17.310
or it will fuse with other chromosomes.

00:18:17.310 --> 00:18:19.770
So they were the first to
functionally define the telomere

00:18:19.770 --> 00:18:21.300
as we just described it.

00:18:22.230 --> 00:18:26.380
Then it was in the 1970s
that Elizabeth Blackburn,

00:18:26.380 --> 00:18:28.270
working together with Joe Gall,

00:18:28.270 --> 00:18:31.540
showed the molecular
characteristics of the telomere.

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:34.790
So they defined the actual
DNA sequence at the time.

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:37.240
Then understanding that
molecular characteristic,

00:18:37.240 --> 00:18:40.050
we could then go forward
and ask questions about

00:18:40.050 --> 00:18:42.250
how the end of the
chromosome is maintained.

00:18:47.283 --> 00:18:48.183
- Explain a little more what understanding

00:18:49.930 --> 00:18:54.020
the end and the molecular
structure at the end,

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:55.850
what is that about?

00:18:55.850 --> 00:18:59.480
In other words, it's,

00:19:00.370 --> 00:19:02.720
Help me understand that.

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:07.220
- If you understand the detailed
make-up of the chromosome,

00:19:07.220 --> 00:19:09.920
then that allows one to do experiments

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:12.050
to be able to test how is it

00:19:12.050 --> 00:19:14.150
that the end of the
chromosome can be maintained.

00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:17.750
But if you don't know what
it functionally is made of,

00:19:17.750 --> 00:19:20.570
then you can't design
experiments around that.

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:23.960
So, it was really understanding
that DNA sequence,

00:19:23.960 --> 00:19:27.390
and, in the case of the telomere sequence

00:19:27.390 --> 00:19:28.990
that Liz Blackburn defined,

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:32.770
it was from the ciliated
protozoan Tetrahymena,

00:19:32.770 --> 00:19:35.490
which has 40,000 chromosomes.

00:19:35.490 --> 00:19:38.080
- So you pick a one-cell organism

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:39.710
that's doing a lot of this work.

00:19:39.710 --> 00:19:40.620
- Exactly.

00:19:40.620 --> 00:19:42.930
It's got 40,000 chromosomes,
so you go to the source

00:19:42.930 --> 00:19:47.410
to find out what the
material is actually made of.

00:19:47.410 --> 00:19:52.040
They found that it was this
very simple, repeated sequence.

00:19:52.040 --> 00:19:55.090
In DNA we use the four-letter alphabet

00:19:55.090 --> 00:19:58.030
for the building blocks of the DNA.

00:19:58.030 --> 00:20:00.300
And that's T, C, A and G.

00:20:00.300 --> 00:20:02.050
But what they found was that this telomere

00:20:02.050 --> 00:20:07.050
was made up of a very, very
repetitive TTGGGG TTGGGG TTGGGG.

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:10.770
Hundreds of repeats.

00:20:10.770 --> 00:20:13.050
Very, very simple and repetitive,

00:20:13.050 --> 00:20:14.090
and that that's what actually

00:20:14.090 --> 00:20:17.400
provides the protective cap
at the end of the chromosome.

00:20:17.400 --> 00:20:21.880
- Does that mean that the cap
is made up of individual caps

00:20:21.880 --> 00:20:24.300
or it's one continuous structure?

00:20:24.300 --> 00:20:25.970
- It's one continuous structure and then

00:20:25.970 --> 00:20:30.290
that DNA sequence actually has
proteins that bind along it

00:20:30.290 --> 00:20:32.730
to carry out the function of the telomere.

00:20:34.930 --> 00:20:39.640
- Do different organisms
have different lengths

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:42.750
and then, throughout the aging process,

00:20:42.750 --> 00:20:45.250
what happens to these caps?

00:20:45.250 --> 00:20:46.760
- At first it was only identified

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:49.220
in these single-cell ciliates and then,

00:20:49.220 --> 00:20:51.420
as more people started doing experiments,

00:20:51.420 --> 00:20:55.280
one you know what an initial sequence is,

00:20:55.280 --> 00:20:57.000
then it gives you something in mind

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:59.070
to look in other organisms.

00:20:59.070 --> 00:21:00.680
So, one of the very nice things

00:21:00.680 --> 00:21:03.980
about working on something as
fundamental as the telomere

00:21:03.980 --> 00:21:07.110
is that things that are that
fundamental inside cells

00:21:07.110 --> 00:21:10.330
tend to be conserved
throughout organisms and so,

00:21:10.330 --> 00:21:12.220
how it's solved in one organism

00:21:12.220 --> 00:21:14.670
will tend to be true in
many, many organisms.

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:18.700
It turned out that that was
very true for telomeres.

00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:20.640
So as people started identifying

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:23.120
telomere sequences in different organisms,

00:21:23.120 --> 00:21:25.430
there were also these simple, repeated

00:21:25.430 --> 00:21:28.610
sequences on the ends of chromosomes.

00:21:28.610 --> 00:21:31.710
So, we were able to
then do more experiments

00:21:31.710 --> 00:21:34.550
to try and understand
how those are maintained.

00:21:36.820 --> 00:21:39.910
- Blackburn and her associate, Gall,

00:21:42.619 --> 00:21:47.330
part of their experimentation
which really pushed this along

00:21:47.330 --> 00:21:51.350
was the discovery

00:21:51.350 --> 00:21:54.340
that you could take one organism

00:21:54.340 --> 00:21:58.640
and, essentially, build caps

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:02.160
in another related organism,
but a different organism.

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:03.560
- So that was the experiment
that had been done

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:06.500
just before I came to
Berkeley and that was

00:22:06.500 --> 00:22:09.180
a collaboration of Liz
Blackburn with Jack Szostak

00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:12.520
and they took a piece of DNA from yeast,

00:22:12.520 --> 00:22:14.380
which is normally a circle,

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:15.990
and then they opened that circle

00:22:15.990 --> 00:22:18.750
and added the telomeres
that they had identified,

00:22:18.750 --> 00:22:20.890
that Liz had identified from Tetrahymena.

00:22:20.890 --> 00:22:22.920
So, instead of a circle, they now had

00:22:22.920 --> 00:22:26.000
what would be a linear
chromosome, like most chromosomes.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:27.640
Quite remarkably, they found that

00:22:27.640 --> 00:22:30.650
when they took that linear
piece of DNA with telomeres

00:22:30.650 --> 00:22:33.010
and put it inside yeast cells,

00:22:33.010 --> 00:22:34.390
and Tetrahymena and yeast are

00:22:34.390 --> 00:22:36.700
in two different kingdoms of life,

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:39.300
that that function,
that telomere function,

00:22:39.300 --> 00:22:41.100
was maintained inside the yeast.

00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:42.520
So the telomeres functioned

00:22:42.520 --> 00:22:44.730
and you now had this linear chromosome.

00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:48.510
That was really a key experiment,
but even more importantly,

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:50.660
was then going and looking to see,

00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:54.440
within those yeast cells,
that Tetrahymena telomere

00:22:54.440 --> 00:22:57.990
had a little bit of telomere
sequences added onto it

00:22:57.990 --> 00:23:01.750
that were yeast-specific
sequences as it was dividing.

00:23:01.750 --> 00:23:04.640
And that provided the clue

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:08.730
that made Liz and Jack
suggest this mechanism,

00:23:08.730 --> 00:23:11.770
how is it that telomeres
are actually maintained?

00:23:11.770 --> 00:23:14.910
They made the very bold
proposal that, maybe,

00:23:14.910 --> 00:23:18.170
there is an enzyme that actually will just

00:23:18.170 --> 00:23:22.070
add these repeated sequences
onto the ends of chromosomes.

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:24.480
So, as I said, normally you
would expect the telomeres

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:27.580
to shorten progressively
with each cell division,

00:23:27.580 --> 00:23:30.010
but they proposed that, if
you can then add something,

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:32.920
then you can balance out the
shortening with addition.

00:23:32.920 --> 00:23:35.490
So that's what I then set out to test

00:23:35.490 --> 00:23:38.190
when I came to work with Liz Blackburn.

00:23:38.190 --> 00:23:41.460
- Just out of curiosity, is the sequence

00:23:41.460 --> 00:23:44.030
in the different organisms the same?

00:23:44.030 --> 00:23:45.340
- It's not exactly the same.

00:23:45.340 --> 00:23:46.730
It's the same flavor.

00:23:46.730 --> 00:23:49.060
That is, it's tandemly repeated sequences.

00:23:49.060 --> 00:23:52.060
But, very conveniently, the yeast sequence

00:23:52.060 --> 00:23:55.000
is just slightly different
than the Tetrahymena sequence.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:58.020
So you could see that you
had Tetrahymena telomeres

00:23:58.020 --> 00:24:00.230
and then there was a
transition into yeast telomeres

00:24:00.230 --> 00:24:03.310
at the very end of the sequence,

00:24:03.310 --> 00:24:05.310
which allowed them then to propose

00:24:05.310 --> 00:24:08.150
that they could be added by an enzyme.

00:24:08.150 --> 00:24:11.680
- So, okay, you're a
first-year graduate student.

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:16.680
You've studied enough to
know who you wanna study with

00:24:17.380 --> 00:24:22.380
and you have been exposed to the history

00:24:22.430 --> 00:24:25.220
that we've just talked
about in terms of discovery.

00:24:25.220 --> 00:24:29.780
So then what did you say to yourself

00:24:29.780 --> 00:24:32.730
about what you wanted to focus on?

00:24:32.730 --> 00:24:35.590
- For first-year graduate
students, at least at the time,

